Wednesday August 28th 2013 9:22 pm -04:00,As I peruse the questions about Assignment 1 that have been asked in this discussion forum so far Im struck by how much more complicated other peoples solutions seemingly are versus the solutions I came up with. So I thought Id offer some helpful advice to those fellow students who might be struggling because frankly theyre making the problems harder than they need to be.The instructions state plainly Each function body will be quite short. This is true. Indeed each one of my function bodies is just a single statement.All the user-defined functions can be written without using any built-in functions.Theres nothing in the instructions about needing to round or truncate any numbers explicitly.The key to solving several of the problems is to use exactly the right arithmetic operator.There are 60 seconds in a minute and 3600 seconds in an hour. These values are constants. It isnt necessary to compute the number of seconds in an hour within any user-defined functions.In the Preface the instructors explain that [a] problem domain is an area of expertise that needs to be understood in order to solve a problem. â€¦ Every assignment in this course will have a problem domain that you will need to learn about. To write the functions for Assignment 1 you really dont have to know any more about time zones and Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) than is explained in the Preface. As it happens its more important to know simple time arithmeticâ€”the kind you learned in grade school.Remember the KISS principle.I hope this advice is helpful. I suppose if it is or isnt will be reflected by the vote tally you see below.JimUPDATE (2013-08-30 00:40 UTC): Also check out my post titled Helpful Resource: Fun With Modular Arithmetic. , Pinned Resolved,130
