Thursday September 12th 2013 4:03 am -04:00,Sure. But if you implement the solution in a particular way then you dont have to test for the empty string explicitly. The empty string is just included among the default cases for which the Boolean value returned by the function is True. The default    case is defined as any string consisting solely of zero or more occurrences of the characters A T C and G.In my opinion this is the simplest most elegant implementation. Inspect each character (nucleotide) in the string (DNA sequence) in turn from first to last. If the character is not one of A T C or G then return False immediately short-circuiting    the needless inspection of any more characters. Otherwise after inspecting all the (valid) characters in the string return True., Resolved,3
Thursday September 12th 2013 8:24 pm -04:00,It would have been clearer and resulted in less confusion among the students if the Assignment 2 instructions had stated plainly The empty string  is a valid DNA sequence. Let us stipulate this painfully obvious fact. Those who insist that the instructions are crystal clear and unambiguous are mistaken. This is also quite obvious from the mere existence of this and at least one other lengthy thread in the discussion forum. Now to the heart of the matter. Is it wrong to regard nothingness (i.e. the empty string) as a valid DNA sequence? The answer is unequivocally it depends.In the case of a DNA sequence in the natural world its seems obvious even to someone like me who knows very little about biology that a DNA sequence must consist of something if it is to be considered a viable DNA sequence. So let us also stipulate this obvious fact of biology.But a computer program is a kind of model of something in the natural world; its not the thing itself. And computer programs very often must allow for small accommodationsâ€”fudgesâ€”at the boundaries of the model just to make things work.Heres a simple example albeit perhaps a silly one. In the real world theres no such thing as a college class with no students in it. If no one exists to learn then no education can possibly occur. Therefore the definition of a college class includes an assumption of one or more students. But a computer program that models college classes professors students grades etc. will nonetheless allow a variable named say number_of_students_in_class to refer to the value 0. Indeed it will probably always have the initial value 0 because in the model the college class will exist before any students are enrolled in it. Youd be stuck with a real dilemma if the count of the number of students enrolled in the class (in the model of the class) could never be 0. It would be unworkable.Hopefully Ive made it easier for you to imagine a reason why in a computer program an empty string might be a valid value for something like a DNA sequence as a simple expedient.Jim, Resolved,15
